This was fine with the shadow DOM disabled.

@nathansobo this feels like a big deal, but maybe there were actually no memory leaks caused.

If you copy this code:

```
function test(a) {
  switch(a) {
    case 1:
      console.log('one');
      break;
    case 2:
      console.log('two');
      break;
    default:
      console.log('uh oh');
  }
}
```

and then try to paste it into a javascript file in Atom, you get this:

```
function test(a) {
  switch(a) {
    case 1:
      console.log('one');
      break;
      case 2:
        console.log('two');
        break;
        default:
          console.log('uh oh');
        }
      }

```

